<font color="#FF0000">REFLECTION WITH HONOR</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug 13 14:05:39 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
THERE CAN BE NO GREATER HONOR THEN TO BE HONORED BY THOSE YOU SERVED WITH!!!<br><br>
First Marine Division Assocation Reunion<br>
August 4-10, 1997, Those present were Marines that participated in operation DeSoto (The Gates of Hell), Foster (Arizona Territory) Rock (Charlie's Ridge), Mamaluke Thrust (Dodge City &amp; Go Noa Island).<br><br>
I rented a suite for our company and we all gathered, many brought their photo albums, some brought their wives, doc brought his son, others their memories, only one suffered from PTSD. 37 attended and it was one of the most memorable days in my life. <br>
One of the high lights occurred; <br>
Saturday morning in San Antonio, Texas we gathered at Greg Van De Walle Park named after a Marine in 1st platoon, India Company killed on May 14, 1967. <br>
The night he died his mother across the sea turned and said to her husband, our son is dead. I just heard him call my name and Judy's name (his girl friend).<br>
Less then 12 hours later, a Marine lieutenant came to their front door to notify them of their son's death.<br><br>
The family and 37 Marines from India Company had gathered 30 years after his death to honor him, during our reunion. The Captain called us to attention and issued his last command (He, is dying of cancer, and is loved and admired by the men under his command). We fell into column and at his command presented arms.<br><br>
At the entrance to the park are the last words that Marine wrote in his last letter home. The words are embossed on a brass plate at the entrance to the park.<br><br>
World's Best War machine<br><br>
You sit at home and watch TV,<br>
And sip a glass of icy tea.<br>
The news comes on and then you hear<br>
The All-Star game is drawing near.<br>
Then you see a far-off land<br>
Where men are dying in the sand.<br>
Forget the guy across the sea,<br>
He's far away and doesn't concern me.<br>
He's waging a war<br>
To keep the fight from your door.<br>
Do you realize what he'll do?<br>
Like giving up his life for you.<br>
Yet he asks nothing in return,<br>
So you can stay in school and learn.<br>
The college crowd thinks he is a fool,<br>
That's what makes him hard and cruel.<br>
Some will be heroes because they're brave, <br>
Others will earn an earthen grave.<br>
You'll spot him as he passes by,<br>
There is a sad, but proud look in his eye.<br>
He's the world's best war machine - - <br>
He's a United States marine.<br><br>
Some time after his death, a war protester (same as resister, same as peace demonstrator, same as coward, same as conscientious objector, same as etc….) called Ms. Van De Walle and informed her that they were going to read out loud his name in protest as having died in vain in Vietnam.<br><br>
Ms. Van De Walle marched into the midst of the protesters group and said, <br>
&quot;You will not dishonor my sons name, he did not die in vain, he died for what he believed in and was proud to be a Marine. They never spoke his name that day. <br><br>
After the brief memorial service, I stole a glance at the middle-aged men who had gathered around to eat, speak, and share fond memories of a lost warrior. <br>
They all looked so mellow, their hair brushed with various shades of gray, their eyes full of compassion, understanding and love for life and for their fellowmen. Yet I could not help but see them as I had thirty years before. Young Marines, fighting battle -savvy North Vietnamese communist soldiers for the right to live. Anyone looking upon them would find it hard to believe that these same middle aged men had reeked so much death, destruction, pain, and sorrow upon the enemy. <br>
That is one honor that cannot be shared with others it has no place of posting here, where America's shame resides. There can be no dialog with weak hearts, deceitful minds, truth cannot reside in the hearts of cowards who choose what battles they deem worthy, while their fellow men carried the yoke of freedom. No communication can truly exists or be understood while such individuals hide under the shadows of the Constitution and proclaim their right to be heard.<br><br>
We killed communist gooks, killed many, many of them, killed them with our knives, our hands, red-hot tracers and called in napalm from the sky that melted their facial and human features away. We fought them for the right to live and accomplish what our country called us to do. We believed then and still do today that it was a worthy cause. A worthy war that should have been fought to win. No one died in vain in Vietnam, that war was another battle in the cold war we finally won. Not one of us regretted having fought, having killed atheistic communist gooks. The war we waged, I have found did not bother us. We did not suffer from its pains, from the memories of war. Where we suffered the most was from what occurred afterwards in the battles waged at home where the stars and stripes were burned and draft dodgers referred to as heroes of the new age. That, we could not understand. It was not the country we knew and fought for. <br>
.<br>
I have come to realize that there are no gray lines in real wars. No truce or demilitarized zones. We fight for what is right or we suffer the shame of failure and that is what we did. It is with those memories of honorable men that I realize this dialog is useless, useless because it will not change history. It will not changed the hearts of the cowards that ran and hide while honorable men paid the ultimate price for freedom. These cowards were not soldiers to be honored by my involvement with them, they can never understand what we shared, they will never be able to partake of those honors and the friendship forged in the heat of battle. They can never be trusted in any battle call for justice or freedom. <br><br>
Gee, I love those men with whom I fought in battle against the enemy. They hold their heads held high; they did not fight for the medals and ribbons of war. They received much more then that, they received the honor of the men they served with. We fought a worthy foe with honor, killed the enemy with honor and afterwards suffered the pains of hell with honor. Yet, nothing, nothing in our youth, in our military training prepared us for the madness at home for the deceitfulness waged in our back yards and that too we endured with honor and silence. <br><br>
We don't hide our involvement, or our names, we are not silent warriors but proud of our involvement and share our victories and pains with those who walked our flanks and points, who supported us from the ground, from above, and from the sea and in the rear. What we accomplished in the jungles of South East Asia, history will continue to unveil. Ironically, it is our former enemies who have begun to honor us with their submission to the goals we sought. <br><br>
Today we have begun to climb out of the rice paddies at home where we have been pinned down all these years. We will not look back but will move forward, pulling other Vietnam veterans out of the mud of shame; they have been unjustifiably covered with. We will move forward and expose those who failed to do what they knew in their hearts was right but choose instead to blame the veteran for their failure to defend their country. Individuals who failed to fight for the rights and love for freedom others craved across the sea and because of this many Americans died because of this many Asians from Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos were abandoned and we lost our glory and the right to be heard by the nations of the world. <br><br>
I'm Cook Barela and those are my thoughts <br><br>

<p><code>-- India Co. 3/7, USMC, June 67-July 68, RVN  (Cook Barela) </code><p>


